# VarLens Concept Pilot — operator secrets (Layer 2)
#
# Copy to web-deploy/.env (chmod 600) and fill in. This file is the
# single place an operator types their bring-up secrets. `pilot.sh`
# sources it before preflight so values are available across shells
# without re-exporting every session. Shell exports still override —
# `export GHCR_TOKEN=...` in the running shell beats whatever this file
# says, so CI / one-off runs keep working unchanged.
#
# Layer split (see .planning/web/phase2-followup-operator-env.md):
#   - web-deploy/.env             (this file) — operator-typed secrets
#   - web-deploy/compose/.env     (server-only) — runtime config docker
#                                                 compose consumes
#   - web-deploy/tofu/.../tfvars  — Hetzner API token + ssh_pubkey
#                                   (different lifecycle, stays separate)

# --- GHCR (private varlens-web image pull) ------------------------------------
# GitHub PAT (classic) with read:packages scope. Piped to `docker login`
# stdin on the server during stack-up; never written to disk on the server.
GHCR_TOKEN=
# GitHub username that owns the GHCR package; defaults to "robspan".
GHCR_USER=

# --- Hetzner Object Storage (restic backup target) ----------------------------
# REQUIRED. Hetzner does NOT expose an API for S3 credential creation
# (probed 2026-05-07: /v1/object_storage/credentials returns 404). The
# keypair is generated once per account in the console and pasted here.
# Bucket creation and restic-repo setup are automated downstream — this
# is the only manual step in the bring-up.
#
# Generate ONCE: Hetzner Console > Security > S3 Credentials > Generate
# (the secret is shown only at generation time; capture both immediately).
RESTIC_S3_ACCESS_KEY=
RESTIC_S3_SECRET_KEY=

# --- VarLens admin bootstrap (one-shot, first-boot only) ----------------------
# When BOTH username and password are set on the FIRST stack-up against a
# fresh data volume, the VarLens app creates an Argon2 admin user and
# writes a one-time recovery key to /mnt/data/app/data/admin-recovery-key.txt.
# After capturing that file:
#   1. Delete the file from the server (operator's "I have it" signal).
#   2. Blank these two values here (leaving displayName is fine).
#      The container has them in its env, but post-bootstrap they're
#      ignored with a WARN log — keeping them around just lengthens
#      the time the plaintext password lives in `docker inspect` output.
#
# Rotation via these env vars is NOT supported (see server.ts:F7
# diagnostic). Future: `varlens admin rotate`.
VARLENS_ADMIN_USERNAME=
VARLENS_ADMIN_PASSWORD=
VARLENS_ADMIN_DISPLAY_NAME=
